The problem asks to prove that the solution set $S$ to the inequality $\sum_{k=1}^{70} \frac{k}{x-k} \ge \frac{5}{4}$ is a union of disjoint intervals with total length 1988.
We define the polynomial $Q(x) = 5 \prod_{k=1}^{70}(x-k) - 4 \sum_{k=1}^{70} k \prod_{j \ne k} (x-j)$.
The roots of $Q(x)$ are exactly the right endpoints of the intervals (the roots of the equation $\sum \frac{k}{x-k} = \frac{5}{4}$).
The sum of the roots of $Q(x)$ can be found by Vieta's formulas.
The coefficient of $x^{70}$ in $Q(x)$ is $5$.
The coefficient of $x^{69}$ in $Q(x)$ is $-5 \sum k - 4 \sum k = -9 \sum k$.
Thus, the sum of the roots is $\frac{9}{5} \sum_{k=1}^{70} k$.
The total length of the intervals is $\sum (r_k - l_k) = \sum r_k - \sum k = \frac{9}{5} S_1 - S_1 = \frac{4}{5} S_1$.
With $S_1 = \frac{70 \times 71}{2} = 2485$, the total length is $\frac{4}{5} \times 2485 = 1988$.

